We have elected to use a carry-bypass adder. In this case we group by every 4 bits, and for each 4 bits we calculate whether the 4 bits would propagate the Cin. This means that the worst case would be when Cin must ripple through all four of the muxes. This then leads to our our critical path which is precisely when we must propagate through all of the muxes. This is when all of A are 0 and all of B are one and we toggle Cin. 

Some other design decisions we made was to reuse the XOR for both P and the actual XOR output. We do the same for generate which is our AND. We have a 4 by 1 mux for every bit.  


Propagation Delay Calculations: We were able to extract all the parasitics from the entire ALU.gds file, but this was too large to run on xschem. Therefore, we tested the critical path and propagation delay on the 4bit block and used this value to extrapolate for the entire ALU. The critical path we found was from Cin to Cout, when Cin propagates all the way through to Cout.

Prop Delay for 4bitblock: 1.274483e-10

Therefore, entire critical path prop delay:
t_c \approx 4*t_{4bit} = 4*1.274483e-10 = 0.51ns

This is obviously an approximately but we believe it is a very accurate one as the final gates at the end add very little additional delay.

Important files:

tbs/alu_4bitblock_critical_path.sch -> This is the testbench for calculating the critical path propagation delay for 4 bit block
SUBMIT/spice_4bitblock_propdelay.png -> Image taken of the propagation delay between Cin and Cout for the 4bit block

tbs/alu_critical_path.sch -> this contains the critical path testbench for the entire alu which will not run given the length of the extracted netlist
tbs/alu_tb_add.sch -> this contains the testbench for adding two numbers
tbs/alu_tb_add_overflow.sch -> this contains the testbench for adding two numbers large enough that there should be overflow
tbs/alu_tb_sub.sch -> this contains the testbench for subtracting two numbers
tbs/alu_tb_subtract_overflow.sch -> this testbench tests subtracting two values that should return a negative number and not produce an overflow
tbs/alu_tb_cmpe.sch -> this testbench tests comparing two values that are equal and ensuring the z flag is set
tbs/alu_tb_cmpne.sch -> This testbench tests when comparing two values that are not equal and thus the n flag should be set and z shouldn't

Note: some of the tests it was asking for such as adding 1 to -1 said that it should produce an overflow flag, but I believe that this is a mistake as we are dealing with signed integers. Nonetheless, we added another testL alu_tb_add_overflow which tests an actual combination that should indeed overflow.

SUBMIT/ALU_antenna_drc.png -> Contains the succesfull ALU antenna drc results
SUBMIT/ALU_density_drc.png -> contains the successful ALU density drc result
SUBMIT/ALU_lvs.png -> successful LVS for ALU
SUBMIT/ALU_main_drc.png -> successful main drc
SUBMIT/hand_draing_criticalpath.png -> contains the drawing for the critical path which uses the extrapolated data for the single 4bitblock and shows how this signal propagates through the entire ALU.

Note: for testing the ALU output we didn't use waveforms. Instead we wrote an algorithm to actually output the resulting data as an integer this was much quicker then manually verifying correct waveform output.
SUBMIT/spice_adding_tb_verified.png -> shows correct output for adding two values
SUBMIT/spice_adding_overflow.png -> shows overflow flag being raised correctly
SUBMIT/spice_adding_positive_to_neative.png -> Shows adding a positive 1 to -1 which should return 0 and should raise no flags
SUBMIT/spice_subtract_easy.png -> shows correct subtraction functionality
SUBMIT/spice_subtracting_1_from_0_works.png -> shows we can flip all the bits and still not worry about an overflow flag
SUBMIT/spice_cmp_ne_raiseN_dont_raiseZ.png -> Shows correct compare functionality where we have two non equal inputs which raise N but not Z
SUBMIT/spice_cmp_z_flag_raised.png -> shows comparing two integers that are equal raises z flag.

The rest of the images submitted show the additional work we did to ensure that the ALU functioned correctly but was not part of one of the explicit deliverables.


